                          <tr>
                            <td valign="top" style="font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color:#333333; font-size:12px; text-align:justify;">As you sit ogling at colorful ads on new property promoted by big names and salivating at the prospect of interest rates for home loans coming down - dreaming about owning a cozy little apartment or a plush duplex - and considering which bank you should patronize by borrowing from them - stop!<br />
                              <br />
                              What makes you think you will actually get that loan? <br />
  <br />
                              Lending institutions like banks have begun checking CIBIL records of every loan applicant before approving loans. So if you are applying for a loan with a bank, CIBIL (Credit Information Bureau of India Ltd) who maintains your loan history and repayment behavior will report to the bank - details of what all loans you have and how you are treating those lenders. In fact, even details of whether you are paying your phone bills on time! And if you have a messed up record with any one bank, that record is there for all to see and all other lenders can refuse to lend to you.<br />
  <br />
                              And even if you have been paying off all your loans on time, never paid a penalty or late fee and never ever rolled over credit cards your CIBIL report could look ugly. And that is the twist in the tale. <br />
  <br />
                              Sometimes CIBIL reports could go against you because of wrong reports and erroneous updates. We are seeing cases of mix up of names, somebody else living in the same address has not repaid their dues and so the loan application gets rejected, some credit card fees has been outstanding and accumulating interest that has ballooned to be a scary figure and many such weird incidences. <br />
  <br />
                              Correcting these errors and rebuilding the credit score can take anywhere between 3 months to 1 year. <br />
  <br />
                              And that means - 3 months to 1 year delay in getting that loan. Postponing purchase of your assets might result in prices of the assets going up in the mean time. Worse still, if you were planning to take a loan for other things like education or to tide over urgent personal needs.... <br />
  <br />
                              To avoid such situations, strongly recommend you check your credit rating with CIBIL proactively. And get some help to understand the heavily jargonized report. <br />
  <br />
                              Talk to your financial planner about this.  A good credit health is the first step to great financial health. Let nothing stop you from achieving your goals.</td>
